    "biography": {
      "value": "<p>The Barrow-Wight is what a Barrow-Warden becomes when left too long without purpose -- when the burial-oath calcifies into something older and crueler. Taller than any living man, wearing funerary iron corroded to black, it carries the frost-etched blade of its original charge.</p><p>Unlike the thralls it commands, the Barrow-Wight remembers what it was. That memory is the wound. It speaks in Old Norrœnt, accusing the living of transgressions against the dead, holding court in darkness with the authority of something that was once honoured and is now only ancient.</p><p>The runic inscriptions in the barrow-complex below Stairwatch reference \"the binding below\" and \"the wolf that waits\" -- Grafvitnir lore. The Wight is one of the oldest seals in this system: a guardian placed here before Svellheim existed, warding something deeper.</p>",
      "director": "<p>The Barrow-Wight acts twice per round (turns: 2). Open with Wight's Blade on the most armoured target, then Soul Grip on a caster or support. Use Binding Rune (3 Malice) when a key PC is about to use a major ability. Hold Barrow's Call (5 Malice) for mid-fight -- summon thralls when the PCs think they're winning.</p><p>Environmental hazards (unstable ceiling, flooded passages, choking dust) complicate the encounter. The two living miners are behind a cave-in three rooms deep. The dead miner lies near the runic chamber entrance. The Wight guards the runic chamber.</p>",
      "languages": []
